</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">As automated breast (AB) US becomes more integrated into the daily practice of breast imaging, the need to address the artifacts that interfere with AB US image interpretation is becoming more important. Learning methods to detect and subsequently resolve artifacts such as shadowing can enhance the reader’s confidence and ability to differentiate artifacts and true abnormalities. Understanding the basic principles of AB US and its image acquisition process are key elements in resolving artifacts. Gaining familiarity with the common patterns of AB US artifacts and placing them into categories of technical, software, physiologic, and breast lesion–related causes can aid in image interpretation. Recognizing specific artifacts, such as dropout and lack of contact, and the ability to distinguish them from true abnormalities, such as surgical scars and suspicious lesions, can help minimize preventable false-positive interpretations. Applying methods to confirm shadowing as artifactual, including the use of a second view, additional planes, and software-related tools such as the rotational tool, can aid the radiologist in resolving artifacts and avoiding preventable recalls, potentially resulting in increased specificity. Presented is a methodical approach to recognizing AB US artifacts and their causes; analyzing shadowing, a challenging entity in the interpretation of AB US imaging studies; differentiating artifact from true abnormality; and reviewing characteristic patterns and basic techniques to resolve artifacts. The goal of this article is to enable the radiologist in applying these methods to help reduce preventable false-positive recommendations and increase efficiency in AB US image interpretation.</div><div role="paragraph"><i><a href="https://pubs.rsna.org/do/10.1148/rg.2019180104.pres/full/">Online supplemental material is available for this article.</a></i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2019</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180104">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180104">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig1.jpeg" height="2171" width="2990" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. AB US image acquisition. AB US images are acquired by using a wide high-resolution linear transducer (top), which has a much wider footprint (15.4 cm) than the transducer used for HH US (5.8 cm) (bottom). In the middle, an AB US image is shown with an HH US image (enclosed in rectangle) overlying it. The images show an irregular hypoechoic mass in crosshairs (grade 2 invasive ductal carcinoma with mucin production) with surrounding architectural distortion. Note how much more surrounding tissue is depicted on the AB US image than on the HH US image of the same mass in the same position (arrows). On the upper half of the overlying HH image, opacity is graded as highest on the right to transparent on the left, exposing the underlying AB US image and demonstrating the reproducibility of image findings that is achievable with both techniques.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig2.jpeg" height="2438" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Transducer positioning to acquire the views covering the breast tissue at AB US. Three scans of each breast are usually obtained: the AP, LAT, and MED views. Left: Diagrams illustrate the volumes of breast tissue captured in each view, with the AP view overlapping centrally with the LAT and MED views. Middle: Photographs show proper patient positioning and transducer placement for each view. (Adapted and reprinted, with permission, from Siemens Medical Solutions.) Right: Coronal planes demonstrate the coverage of breast tissue in relation to the scanning position. Yellow circles denote the location of the nipple in each view.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig3.jpeg" height="1101" width="2690" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Acquisition of initially obtained transverse (<i>X</i>) image set (left) and reconstruction of the software-generated sagittal (<i>Y</i>) and coronal (<i>Z</i>) planes (right). Images are captured in the transverse orientation (green arrows) by using a wide AB US transducer (top left). After the acquisition, the software reconstructs two additional orthogonal planes in sagittal and coronal directions (blue arrow). The transverse image shows a hypoechoic, oval, circumscribed mass, representing a fibroadenoma, which is also seen on the three-dimensional reconstructed layers. The uppermost sectioned coronal plane appears to be hyperechoic at the superficial level, representing the skin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig4.jpeg" height="1348" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Anatomic correlation of the three displayed AB US planes. The three orthogonal planes (left) are displayed in one of a number of hanging protocols (right). The position in each of the software-reconstructed planes, the sagittal <i>(Y)</i> and coronal <i>(Z)</i> planes, is matched with the position in the originally acquired transverse <i>(X)</i> image set. The hypoechoic circumscribed mass seen in <a href="#fig3">Figure 3</a> is shown here sectioned, in the lower region of the right breast on the coronal image, obtained in an AP view, with the crosshairs switched off. The mass is also seen in focus on the transverse and sagittal images. Additional hypoechoic masses are depicted in this case involving biopsy-proven fibroadenomas. The yellow dot marks the nipple region.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig5.jpeg" height="2149" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Correlation of breast tissue levels seen on AB US coronal and sagittal planes with corresponding anatomic diagrams. The tissue layers depicted on AB US coronal planes are sectioned from the superficial to the deep depth, representing the skin <i>(I),</i> subcutaneous fat lobules <i>(II),</i> fibroglandular tissue <i>(III)</i>, and breast lobules <i>(IV).</i> The coronal images correlate with the frontal anatomic diagram (entirely middle) (reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r9" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r9">9</a>) that shows the breast lobules sectioned to illustrate the intralobular ducts and stroma. The axial mid-breast diagram (top middle) (reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r9" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r9">9</a>) and the sagittal AB US plane (bottom middle) demonstrate the breast tissue from the skin to the chest wall, showing ducts entering the nipple. The nipple and areola are immediately recognizable at the skin in level I (top left). AB US image of level II (bottom left) shows medium-gray fat lobules occupying the subcutaneous layer, with a small amount of echogenic fibroglandular tissue in the outer region of the breast. AB US images of layers III (bottom right) and IV (top right) show predominantly light-gray to white fibroglandular tissue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig6.jpeg" height="2721" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Correlation of Breast Imaging Reporting and Data System (BI-RADS) breast composition patterns with AB US echogenicity distribution patterns. For each category (<i>A, B, C,</i> and <i>D</i>), the echogenicity distribution pattern seen on AB US coronal (bottom row, upper images) and transverse (bottom row, lower images) planes is compared to the correlating composition pattern seen on the mediolateral-oblique mammographic view (top row) of the same breast in the same patient. Fatty <i>(A),</i> scattered fibroglandular <i>(B),</i> heterogeneously dense (at mammography) or heterogeneously echogenic (at AB US) <i>(C),</i> and extremely dense (at mammography) or homogeneously echogenic (at AB US) <i>(D)</i> patterns are seen. In <i>A</i> and <i>B,</i> fat is medium gray, with white connective tissue arcs (Cooper ligaments). In comparison, in <i>C</i> and <i>D,</i> the fibroglandular-to-fat ratio has a greater light-gray–to-white–appearing fibroglandular tissue proportion and darker appearing fat than is seen in <i>A</i> and <i>B.</i><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig7.jpeg" height="1938" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. AB US AP view of the left breast of the patient whose right breast is shown in <a href="#fig4">Figure 4</a>. The reconstructed coronal (<i>Z</i>) plane depicts the entire breast of a patient scanned in the supine position, similar to the positioning during breast surgery. The coronal plane of the AP view best displays architectural distortion and multiple benign-appearing masses, as seen in this case of multiple fibroadenomas. Darker areas represent fatty tissue; the lighter regions, fibroglandular tissue; and the yellow circle, the nipple location. The transverse <i>(X)</i> plane sections three fibroadenomas located in the upper region of the breast, as seen on the coronal plane; the most medial of these fibroadenomas is truncated on the sagittal (<i>Y</i>) plane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig8.jpeg" height="2680" width="3688" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Scanning technique–related artifacts. Top row: Photograph (middle) shows the patient positioned for a right LAT scan; a sponge wedge elevates the patient’s shoulder for optimal positioning. In a case of suboptimal positioning and poor transducer placement, a 2-cm section of right posterior breast tissue is excluded in this LAT view coronal <i>(Z)</i> plane (right). Center row: When a small area of skin is bypassed during the application of coupling lotion and scanned (middle), trapped air can cause a black hole artifact on the coronal plane (right, upper image), as well as repetitive horizontal lines of ringdown at the skin level with shadowing beneath (right, lower image) on the transverse <i>(X)</i> plane. Bottom row: Proper transducer placement (middle) is important for image quality. On the coronal plane, a skin fold (right), seen as an echogenic curve, projects across the upper region of the breast. Yellow circles mark the nipple region. (Photographs were adapted and reprinted, with permission, from Siemens Medical Solutions.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig9.jpeg" height="1569" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Nipple artifact. A software algorithm process enhances the retroareolar area (arrows) on AB US transverse <i>(X),</i> sagittal <i>(Y),</i> and coronal <i>(Z)</i> planes. The retroareolar area is typically more difficult to examine owing to intrinsic shadowing from the nipple. The effectiveness of this algorithm depends on the nipple-areolar complex individual anatomic features.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig10.jpeg" height="1682" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Silhouette artifact. The silhouette algorithm aims to suppress image information outside of the breast. When recognition of the breast contour is obstructed—for example, by a bandage, as in this case—the tissue in this region is replaced by a blackened geometric area (arrows), as shown on AB US transverse <i>(X),</i> sagittal <i>(Y),</i> and coronal <i>(Z)</i> planes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig11.jpeg" height="1599" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Cardiac artifact. Left AB US AP coronal <i>(Z)</i> and sagittal <i>(Y)</i> planes show a cluster of straight lines (arrows) in the cardiac area, which are conspicuous at the posterior aspect of the breast in the mediastinal space. This artifact can occur with tachycardia. <i>X</i> = transverse plane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig12.jpeg" height="1525" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Motion artifact. Multiple straight lines, which are seen predominantly on the coronal <i>(Z)</i> and sagittal <i>(Y)</i> planes, can be caused by patient motion, such as talking or hyperventilating, during scanning. Thus, patients are asked not to talk, cough, or laugh during the AB US transducer movement. Arrows point to multiple vertical (on sagittal plane) and horizontal (on coronal plane) lines spanning the entire image depth. <i>X</i> = transverse plane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig13.jpeg" height="1606" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Skip artifact caused by a fibroadenoma. The transducer compresses and then skips over a firm lesion, causing a linear artifact (arrows), which is best seen on coronal <i>(Z)</i> and sagittal <i>(Y)</i> planes. <i>X</i> = transverse plane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig14.jpeg" height="1719" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Intense enhancement is seen as a round highly echogenic area (red arrow) on the coronal <i>(Z)</i> plane and as an echogenic column (white arrow) posterior to a simple cyst on the transverse <i>(X)</i> and sagittal <i>(Y)</i> planes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig15.jpeg" height="1873" width="2100" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Architectural distortion around a surgical scar, with the typical radiating spiculated appearance (arrow), similar to that at digital breast tomosynthesis, on the coronal <i>(Z)</i> plane, and a visible surgical pathway (arrowhead) leading to the focally thickened skin on the transverse <i>(X)</i> plane. <i>Y</i> = sagittal plane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig16.jpeg" height="2296" width="3200" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Shadowing artifact and true abnormality. Top: Architectural distortion surrounding a surgical scar, with a surgical pathway to the skin. Linear or curvilinear shadowing originating at the skin is characteristic of a surgical scar. Middle: Ringdown artifact at the skin level with shadowing beneath indicates a lack of contact and air, which is caused by the absence of coupling lotion. Bottom: A hypoechoic mass and surrounding architectural distortion within the fibroglandular zone of tissue, with posterior shadowing emanating from the mass, represents an invasive lobular carcinoma <i>(ILC).</i><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig17.jpeg" height="1891" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Peripheral shadowing on right MED view, with crosshairs placed at the 11-o’clock position, 3 cm from the nipple <i>(FN)</i> (yellow circle). Peripheral shadowing appears as an irregular hypoechoic area on the coronal <i>(Z)</i> plane, which correlates with regions of shadowing on the transverse <i>(X)</i> and sagittal <i>(Y)</i> planes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig18.jpeg" height="1871" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Right AP view used as a second view of the same breast, with coordinates in approximately the same location (11 o’clock, 3 cm from the nipple <i>[FN]</i> [yellow circle]), as in <a href="#fig17">Figure 17</a>. Normal fibroglandular breast tissue occupies this area, resolving the shadowing seen on the MED view (in <a href="#fig17">Fig 17</a>) as artifactual. A small cyst seen directly medial to this location on the coronal <i>(Z)</i> plane is also identifiable on the coronal and transverse <i>(X)</i> planes in <a href="#fig17">Figure 17</a>. Another hypoechoic-to-anechoic area is seen at approximately the 9-o’clock position, lateral to the nipple, on the coronal plane. This finding can be elucidated by using the same method used to resolve the area at the 11-o’clock location, by using the LAT view as the second view, to confirm this area as normal breast tissue. <i>Y</i> = sagittal plane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig19.jpeg" height="1675" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Peripheral irregularly shaped area of low echogenicity in crosshairs on the coronal <i>(Z)</i> plane on a left MED view at the 10-o’clock position, 9 cm from the nipple <i>(FN)</i> (yellow circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig20.jpeg" height="1663" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. The location of the area within the crosshairs on the acquired transverse <i>(X)</i> plane and reconstructed sagittal <i>(Y)</i> plane is correlated by the software with the location of the area in focus on the coronal plane in <a href="#fig19">Figure 19</a> to identify and further analyze the same region. The magnified area of shadowing on the transverse plane (within the rectangular outline) shows several short, parallel, alternating hyperechoic and anechoic horizontal lines at the skin level, indicating ringdown with shadowing posteriorly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig21.jpeg" height="1508" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Hypoechoic oval area, demarcated by crosshairs, in the lower central region of the breast on the coronal <i>(Z)</i> plane. Correlating crosshairs mark an amorphous area of shadowing on the transverse <i>(X)</i> plane that shows linear shadowing on the sagittal <i>(Y)</i> plane. Yellow circle marks the nipple region.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig22.jpeg" height="887" width="880" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Software-simulated rotation. The region highlighted in <a href="#fig21">Figure 21</a> is in focus here. The area of shadowing changes in morphology with respect to the superficial fibroglandular tissue when the rotational feature is utilized to simulate rotation around the vertical axis (top). No discrete mass comes into focus. <i>X</i> = transverse plane, <i>Y</i> = sagittal plane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig23.jpeg" height="1839" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Software-simulated tilting. In addition to simulating rotating, simulating changing the insonation plane angle around the horizontal axis, equivalent to tilting an HH probe, enables evaluation of the area surrounding the shadowing (top). The result is the same as that of rotating around the vertical axis, as seen in <a href="#fig22">Figure 22</a>; no discrete mass comes into focus. <i>X</i> = transverse plane, <i>Y</i> = sagittal plane.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig24.jpeg" height="2026" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span>. Refraction shadowing. Crosshairs have been placed on an area of architectural distortion in question on this reconstructed coronal <i>(Z)</i> plane on a right AP view at the 9-o’clock position, 3 cm from the nipple <i>(FN)</i> (yellow circle). Note that the selected area corresponds to a thin linear shadow on the transverse <i>(X)</i> and sagittal <i>(Y)</i> planes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig25.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span>. Refraction shadowing. The sagittal plane in <a href="#fig24">Figure 24</a> is magnified here, with the linear shadows seen originating at the edges of fat lobules and other curved surfaces as they intersect with tissue. Periodic repetition of these thin refractive shadows (arrows) is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180104/asset/images/large/rg.2019180104.fig26.jpeg" height="1840" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Shadowing caused by a malignant mass. The shape of the mass is identifiable in all three (transverse <i>[X],</i> sagittal <i>[Y],</i> and coronal <i>[Z])</i> planes. The example shown here illustrates the difference in appearance between shadowing associated with malignancy (in this case, invasive lobular carcinoma <i>[ILC]</i>) and shadowing originating from refraction, as seen in <a href="#fig24">Figures 24</a> and <a href="#fig25">25</a>. AB US images show a single shadow (arrow) originating from the mass itself, rather than from the edges of the mass (as with refraction). The US beam is attenuated during its passage through the carcinoma, causing the shadowing. Similar to the multiple artifactual edge shadows seen in <a href="#fig25">Figure 25</a>, the shadowing seen here is the most conspicuous on the sagittal plane. Yellow circle marks the nipple region. <i>FN</i> = from the nipple, <i>SUP</i> = superior.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180104&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Dempsey PJ. The history of breast ultrasound. <em>J Ultrasound Med</em> 2004;23(7):887–894.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.7863/jum.2004.23.7.887">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15292555/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+history+of+breast+ultrasound&amp;author=PJ+Dempsey&amp;publication_year=2004&amp;journal=J+Ultrasound+Med&amp;pages=887-894&amp;doi=10.7863%2Fjum.2004.23.7.887&amp;pmid=15292555">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Gold RH, Bassett LW, Widoff BE. Highlights from the history of mammography. <em>RadioGraphics</em> 1990;10(6):1111–1131.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/radiographics.10.6.2259767">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2259767/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.g